<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="12" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[113,772,1904,2056]" pageId="13" pageNumber="12">
ETYMOLOGY. The specific epithet is derived from the Latin nominative, singular adjective 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kovařík &amp; Lowe &amp; Stockmann &amp; Šťáhlavský" authorityYear="2020" box="[460,602,1936,1960]" class="Arachnida" family="Chaerilidae" genus="Chaerilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="13" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulcherrimus">
<emphasis box="[460,602,1936,1960]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="12">pulcherrimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(masculine), a superlative of 
<emphasis box="[267,348,1968,1992]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="12">pulcher</emphasis>
= beautiful, in reference to the colorful maculose patterns on the carapace, tergites, metasoma and telson of this diminutive species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
